But the first person to institute the custom of privately dedicating the shields with portraits in a temple or public place, I find, was Appius Claudius, the consul with Publius Servilius in the 259th year of the city. He set up his ancestors in the shrine of the Goddess of VVan and desired thern to be in full view on an elevated spot, and the inscrip- tions stating their honours to be read.
